Final Project - Part 1: Creating Training Dataset¶

Submitted by:¶

  • Roey Gilor
  • Iris Grabov

Introduction¶

In this notebook, we construct a high-quality object detection dataset based on the Flickr image dataset, using the Florence-2 vision-language model. The goal is to prepare data suitable for training a lightweight object detection model (YOLOv8) on edge devices.

The dataset is built in compliance with the course assignment requirements:

  • Bounding boxes are created for the classes: person and pet (union of dog, cat, and horse)
  • Images are split into training and validation sets
  • Annotations are converted to the YOLO format
  • The final dataset is structured for direct compatibility with the Ultralytics YOLOv8 training framework

This part of the project lays the foundation for training and evaluating the detection model in the next phase.

Loading Flickr Images¶

We begin by collecting all available Flickr30k images from the dataset attached via the Kaggle input panel.
These images will be used as the base for annotation using Florence-2.

We use Pathlib to list all .jpg files inside the dataset directory, and store them in a list called all_images, which will be iterated over in the next steps.

Loading Florence-2 on GPU¶

We load the Florence-2 model and its processor using HuggingFace Transformers.
Since we are running in a Kaggle environment with GPU enabled, we move the model to the GPU using .cuda() for faster inference performance.

This setup allows us to run vision-language inference at scale over the Flickr30k dataset.

Automatic Object Annotation with Florence-2 and YOLOv8 Formatting¶

We use the Florence-2 model to automatically annotate each image with object bounding boxes.
To ensure high-quality training data for our YOLOv8 model, we apply a series of constraints known as degrees of freedom.

Goal¶

Generate structured, YOLOv8-compatible annotations for only the relevant classes:

  • person
  • pet (union of dog, cat, horse)

Florence-2 Inference¶

The model generates predictions using a visual-language prompt (e.g., <OD>).
We post-process these predictions to extract:

  • Label name
  • Bounding box in pixel coordinates

Filtering Threshold Decisions (640x480 Images)¶

Object Size Filtering Rationale:¶

Minimum Area (400 pixels):

  • Filters out very small objects (smaller than ~20x20 pixels)
  • At 640x480 resolution, this represents ~3% of image width, ensuring objects are visible and learnable
  • Removes annotation noise while preserving small but valid distant people/pets

Maximum Area (150,000 pixels):

  • Removes extremely large objects (larger than ~387x387 pixels)
  • Prevents objects larger than 60% of image width/80% of image height
  • Maintains focus on well-proportioned objects within the frame

Width Constraints (20-500 pixels):

  • Minimum (20px): ~3% of image width - preserves small objects while removing noise
  • Maximum (500px): ~78% of image width - allows large objects without spanning entire image

Height Constraints (20-400 pixels):

  • Minimum (20px): ~4% of image height - maintains small object detection capability
  • Maximum (400px): ~83% of image height - accommodates tall objects (standing people) while preventing full-frame boxes

Resolution-Specific Considerations:¶

For 640x480 images, these thresholds ensure we capture objects ranging from small pets/distant people (20x20) to large foreground subjects (500x400) while filtering out annotation errors and poorly bounded objects that could hurt model training quality.

This filtering strategy maximizes the accuracy and usability of our YOLOv8 annotations.

Output Format¶

Annotations are saved in the YOLOv8 format:

In [8]:
def generate_yolo_labels_with_scores(task_prompt, image, class_map,
                                     min_box_area=400, max_box_area=150_000,
                                     min_image_width=20, max_image_width=500,
                                     min_image_height=20, max_image_height=400):
    """
    Run Florence-2 on an image, parse output, apply category detection, and return YOLO labels.

    Returns:
        Tuple[List[str], Dict]: (YOLOv8 label lines, parsed Florence-2 output with scores)
    """

    # Filter based on image size
    if not (min_image_width <= image.width <= max_image_width and
            min_image_height <= image.height <= max_image_height):
        return [], {}

    # Florence-2 inference
    inputs = processor(text=task_prompt, images=image, return_tensors="pt").to('cuda', torch.float32)
    output = model.generate(
        input_ids=inputs["input_ids"].cuda(),
        pixel_values=inputs["pixel_values"].cuda(),
        max_new_tokens=1024,
        early_stopping=False,
        do_sample=False,
        num_beams=3,
        return_dict_in_generate=True,
        output_scores=True,
    )

    generated_text = processor.batch_decode(output.sequences, skip_special_tokens=False)[0]
    parsed = processor.post_process_generation(
        generated_text,
        task=task_prompt,
        image_size=(image.width, image.height)
    )

    # Get token-level confidence
    transition_scores = model.compute_transition_scores(
        output.sequences, output.scores, output.beam_indices, normalize_logits=False
    )
    scores = transition_scores[0].cpu().numpy()

    yolo_lines = []
    if "<OD>" in parsed and "bboxes" in parsed["<OD>"]:
        labels = parsed["<OD>"]["labels"]
        bboxes = parsed["<OD>"]["bboxes"]
        num_boxes = len(bboxes)

        if num_boxes > 0:
            split_scores = np.array_split(scores[3:-1], num_boxes)
            box_scores = [float(np.exp(np.mean(s))) for s in split_scores]
            parsed["<OD>"]["scores"] = box_scores

            for label, bbox, score in zip(labels, bboxes, box_scores):
                detected = detect_categories_from_text(label, word_to_category)
                if not detected:
                    continue
                category = detected[0]
                if category not in class_map:
                    continue  #    

                class_id = class_map[category]
                x1, y1, x2, y2 = bbox

                box_w = x2 - x1
                box_h = y2 - y1
                area = box_w * box_h
                if not (min_box_area <= area <= max_box_area):
                    continue

                x_center = (x1 + x2) / 2 / image.width
                y_center = (y1 + y2) / 2 / image.height
                box_w /= image.width
                box_h /= image.height

                yolo_lines.append(f"{class_id} {x_center:.6f} {y_center:.6f} {box_w:.6f} {box_h:.6f}")

    return yolo_lines, parsed.get("<OD>", {})

Visualizing Florence-2 Detections with Bounding Boxes¶

To verify the quality of Florence-2's predictions and the filtering logic applied,
we use a helper function plot_bbox() that draws each predicted bounding box on the image.

What the Visualization Shows¶

  • Bounding boxes for detected objects
  • Class label and confidence score (if available)
  • Red rectangles with annotated class names

This step is useful for:

  • Debugging predictions
  • Validating filtering thresholds (image size, box area, score)
  • Demonstrating annotation quality in our dataset

Each prediction is also mapped to a broader category (person or pet) using a keyword-based matcher.

In [9]:
def plot_bbox(image, data):
   # Create a figure and axes
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()

    # Display the image
    ax.imshow(image)

    bboxes = data.get('bboxes', [])
    labels = data.get('labels', [])
    scores = data.get('scores', [None] * len(labels))
    detected_classes = []

    # Plot each bounding box
    for bbox, original_label, score in zip(bboxes, labels, scores):
      detected = detect_categories_from_text(original_label, word_to_category)
      if not detected:
          continue  #skip
      category = detected[0]
      detected_classes.append(category)

      confidence = f"{score*100:.1f}%" if score is not None else ""
      label_text = f"{category} ({confidence})" if confidence else category

      # Unpack the bounding box coordinates
      x1, y1, x2, y2 = bbox
      # Create a Rectangle patch
      rect = patches.Rectangle((x1, y1), x2-x1, y2-y1, linewidth=1, edgecolor='r', facecolor='none')
      # Add the rectangle to the Axes
      ax.add_patch(rect)
      # Annotate the label
      plt.text(x1, y1, label_text, color='white', fontsize=8, bbox=dict(facecolor='red', alpha=0.5))

    # Remove the axis ticks and labels
    ax.axis('off')
    plt.close(fig)

    return fig, detected_classes

Mapping Florence-2 Labels to YOLO Categories¶

Florence-2 generates detailed natural language labels such as "a man walking his golden retriever."
To train a simpler object detector (e.g., YOLOv8), we need to map these free-text labels to high-level categories:

  • person
  • pet (includes cats, dogs, horses)

Keyword-Based Mapping¶

We define a dictionary word_to_category where each category maps to a list of associated keywords.
The helper function detect_categories_from_text() extracts words from Florence's labels and assigns them to the relevant category.

Example¶

```python text = "A woman playing with her husky in the snow" detect_categories_from_text(text, word_to_category)

➜ ['person', 'pet']¶

        'pony', 'ponies', 'cats', 'dogs', 'horses'

def detect_categories_from_text(text, word_map):
    """
    Detect relevant high-level categories (e.g., 'person', 'pet') based on keywords in the input text.

    Args:
        text (str): Raw input text (label from Florence-2 or similar).
        word_map (dict): Dictionary of {category: [list of associated keywords]}.

    Returns:
        List[str]: Matching categories from the input text.
    """
    text_words = set(re.findall(r"\b\w+\b", text.lower()))
    detected_categories = [
        category for category, keywords in word_map.items()
        if any(word in text_words for word in keywords)
    ]
    return detected_categories

YOLOv8 Dataset Builder with Florence-2 Labels¶

This script generates a YOLOv8-compatible dataset using Florence-2 object detection outputs. It automatically:

Loads and filters images based on size
Runs Florence-2 inference and extracts bounding boxes
Maps detected labels into person and pet categories
Converts results into YOLOv8 format (.txt labels with normalized coordinates)
Saves:

  • The original images
  • The YOLO labels

  • Annotated visualizations (with bounding boxes and confidence)

    Splits data into train and val sets, ensuring class balance (500 train / 100 val per class)

import os
import shutil
from pathlib import Path
from collections import defaultdict
from tqdm.auto import tqdm
from PIL import Image
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import torch  #  Required for memory management

# === CONFIGURATION ===
output_dir = Path("/kaggle/working/dataset_yolo")
task_prompt = "<OD>"
class_map = {"person": 0, "pet": 1}

# Filtering thresholds
# Filtering thresholds for 640x480 images
min_box_area = 400          # pixels (minimum object area)
max_box_area = 150_000      # pixels (maximum object area) 
min_width, max_width = 20, 500     # pixels width range
min_height, max_height = 20, 400   # pixels height range

# Quotas
train_count = 550
val_count = 120

# === CLASS COUNTS TRACKING ===
class_counts = {"train": defaultdict(int), "val": defaultdict(int)}

# === CREATE FOLDERS ===
for split in ["train", "val"]:
    (output_dir / split / "images").mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    (output_dir / split / "labels").mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    (output_dir / split / "annotated").mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# === INIT MULTI-PROGRESS BARS ===
pbar_train_person = tqdm(total=train_count, desc="Train - Person")
pbar_val_person = tqdm(total=val_count, desc="Val   - Person")
pbar_train_pet = tqdm(total=train_count, desc="Train - Pet")
pbar_val_pet = tqdm(total=val_count, desc="Val   - Pet")

# === MAIN IMAGE PROCESSING LOOP ===
for image_path in tqdm(all_images, desc="Building YOLO Dataset"):
    try:
        image = Image.open(image_path).convert("RGB")
    except Exception:
        continue

    try:
        yolo_labels, parsed_output = generate_yolo_labels_with_scores(
            task_prompt, image=image, class_map=class_map,
            min_box_area=min_box_area, max_box_area=max_box_area,
            min_image_width=min_width, max_image_width=max_width,
            min_image_height=min_height, max_image_height=max_height
        )
    except RuntimeError:
        torch.cuda.empty_cache()
        continue

    if not yolo_labels:
        continue

    detected_classes = [
        detect_categories_from_text(lbl, word_to_category)[0]
        for lbl in parsed_output.get("labels", [])
        if detect_categories_from_text(lbl, word_to_category)
    ]
    class_present = list(set(detected_classes) & set(class_map.keys()))
    if not class_present:
        continue

    # === Greedy class-based saving decision ===
    chosen_class, split = None, None
    for cls in class_present:
        if class_counts["train"][cls] < train_count:
            chosen_class = cls
            split = "train"
            break
        elif class_counts["val"][cls] < val_count:
            chosen_class = cls
            split = "val"
            break
    if not chosen_class:
        continue  # all class quotas are full

    # === Save files ===
    label_path = output_dir / split / "labels" / f"{image_path.stem}.txt"
    with open(label_path, "w") as f:
        f.write("\n".join(yolo_labels))

    image.save(output_dir / split / "images" / image_path.name)

    fig = plot_bbox(image, parsed_output)[0]
    fig.savefig(output_dir / split / "annotated" / f"{image_path.stem}_annotated.jpg", dpi=100)
    plt.close(fig)

    # === Update counters ===
    class_counts[split][chosen_class] += 1
    if chosen_class == "person":
        if split == "train":
            pbar_train_person.update(1)
        else:
            pbar_val_person.update(1)
    elif chosen_class == "pet":
        if split == "train":
            pbar_train_pet.update(1)
        else:
            pbar_val_pet.update(1)

    torch.cuda.empty_cache()

    # Stop when all quotas are full
    if all(class_counts["train"][cls] >= train_count for cls in class_map) and \
       all(class_counts["val"][cls] >= val_count for cls in class_map):
        break

# === Close progress bars ===
pbar_train_person.close()
pbar_val_person.close()
pbar_train_pet.close()
pbar_val_pet.close()

# === Final Summary ===
print("\n Dataset creation complete!")
print(" Train counts:", dict(class_counts["train"]))
print(" Val counts:", dict(class_counts["val"]))

# === YAML FILE CREATION ===
yaml_path = output_dir / "dataset.yaml"
yaml_text = f"""path: {output_dir}
train: train/images
val: val/images
names:
  0: person
  1: pet
"""
yaml_path.write_text(yaml_text)
print(" YOLOv8 YAML saved:", yaml_path)

# === ZIP FINAL OUTPUT ===
zip_path = "/kaggle/working/dataset_yolo.zip"
shutil.make_archive(base_name=zip_path.replace(".zip", ""), format="zip", root_dir=output_dir)
print(" Zipped dataset saved to:", zip_path)

 Dataset creation complete!
 Train counts: {'person': 550, 'pet': 550}
 Val counts: {'person': 120, 'pet': 120}
 YOLOv8 YAML saved: /kaggle/working/dataset_yolo/dataset.yaml
 Zipped dataset saved to: /kaggle/working/dataset_yolo.zip

Final Remarks and Annotation Verification Strategies¶

How TTA (Test-Time Augmentations) Can Help Verify Annotations¶

Test-Time Augmentation (TTA) involves applying various transformations (such as flipping, scaling, and rotating) to an image during inference and aggregating the predictions.

To verify annotation correctness using TTA:

  • Apply different augmentations to the same image and run inference.
  • Reverse the augmentations on the predicted boxes to match the original image space.
  • Compare the resulting predictions to the ground-truth annotations.

If the annotations are correct, predictions from various augmentations should consistently align with the labeled objects. Inconsistencies may indicate missing or incorrect annotations, or label ambiguity.

How Ensembles Can Help Validate Training Annotations¶

Ensembling combines the outputs of multiple models (trained independently or with different architectures).

To validate annotations with an ensemble:

  • Run multiple trained models on the same training image.
  • Combine predictions (e.g., using non-maximum suppression with averaged scores).
  • Compare the ensembles aggregated prediction with the annotated labels.

Significant discrepancies between the ensemble output and the annotations may suggest labeling mistakes, such as missing boxes or incorrect class assignments.

Decisions Regarding Degrees of Freedom¶

The dataset generation pipeline applies several constraints to reduce variability and improve data quality:

  • Image filtering by minimum and maximum width and height ensures consistent input resolution.
  • Bounding box area thresholds remove extremely small or large detections that are likely noise.
  • Category filtering limits annotations to relevant classes ("person" and "pet"), reducing label noise.
  • Fixed train and validation sample counts per class ensure balance across splits.

Image filtering by size

min_box_area = 400 # pixels (minimum object area) max_box_area = 150_000 # pixels (maximum object area) min_width, max_width = 20, 500 # pixels width range min_height, max_height = 20, 400 # pixels height range

Filtering Threshold Justification¶

The chosen filtering thresholds (min_box_area=400, max_box_area=150,000, width range 20-500px, height range 20-400px) were carefully selected to balance data quality and quantity for our 640x480 image dataset. The minimum dimensions of 20 pixels preserve small but valid objects such as distant people and small pets, which represent approximately 3-4% of the image dimensions and are commonly encountered in real-world scenarios. This threshold effectively filters out annotation noise while maintaining the diversity of object scales necessary for robust detection performance. The maximum constraints (500px width, 400px height) ensure we focus on well-localized objects rather than scene-level annotations, preventing boxes that span most of the image frame. The area constraints further reinforce these boundaries, creating a dataset that emphasizes properly bounded objects suitable for training an efficient detection model. This conservative approach prioritizes annotation quality over quantity, which is crucial when using Florence-2 generated labels to train a smaller, more efficient model for deployment scenarios.

Category filtering The dataset focuses only on "person" and "pet" categories. These were chosen as relevant, well-defined, and frequently occurring object types in the source dataset. Labels were mapped using keyword matching to ensure consistency across the Florence-2 free-text outputs.

Balanced train/val splits per class To ensure equal representation and avoid class imbalance, we limited each class to:

500 training examples

100 validation examples This controlled sampling supports fair model evaluation and reduces the risk of bias toward any specific class.

These design choices control the degrees of freedom in the data, leading to a cleaner, more structured dataset and more reliable model training. They were selected to balance quality, efficiency, and model readiness for YOLOv8 training and evaluation.
